**Abstract:**
Major essay dated August 16, 1993, titled "First Draft." The document argues that the transformation of theology into an academic discipline in the 12th-13th centuries involved an "eclipse of biblical narrative" comparable to what Frei described in the 17th-18th centuries. Extensively quotes de Lubac's "Exegese Medievale" on the displacement of the Bible from central place in theological studies. It develops a theory of language distinguishing spoken communication (perlocutionary) from written text (illocutionary), arguing that the shift from hearing Scripture as parole vivante de Dieu to reading it as statements to be assented to fundamentally corrupted theological practice.

**AI Recommendation:** Central theoretical essay developing the Chantilly thesis; essential for understanding the author's critique of medieval theology and biblical interpretation.

